PLEASE REPOST THIS ON YOUR STORY
•
Trophy hunting is an epidemic that must be stopped and has several negative impacts. (Swipe to learn more)❤️🦁🦏

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on September 14, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, outdoors and text that says 'REPOST IF YOU ARE AGAINST TROPHY HUNTING SWIPE SWIPE'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on September 14, 2021. May be an image of animal and text that says 'Trophy hunting can hurt the overall population of a species Though hunting groups often claim that a small amount of controlled trophy hunting does not harm populations, the opposite appears to be true.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on September 14, 2021. May be an image of big cat and text that says 'In the case of African lions, "Approximately 600 lions are killed every year on trophy hunts including lions in populations that are already declining from other threats... adult male lion is the most sought-after trophy by wealthy foreign hunters. And when an adult male lion is killed, the destabilization of that lion's pride can lead to more lion deaths as outside males compete to take over the pride, reports Jeff Flocken for National Geographic.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on September 14, 2021. May be an image of rhinoceros, outdoors and text that says 'Does it really bring in money to help the animals and local communities? A study on the economic benefit behind lion hunting in Africa concluded, "The suggestion that trophy hunting plays a significant role in African economic development is misguided...Revenues constitute only a fraction of a percent of GDP and almost none of that ever reaches rural communities."'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on September 14, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, big cat, outdoors and text that says 'Trophy hunting is elitist Since trophy hunting for "big game" usually takes place in more remote locations in which people need to fly into, or charter transportation, it's not really an activity that's open to anyone.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on September 14, 2021. May be an image of rhinoceros, outdoors and text that says 'Trophy hunting can be linked to poaching If trophy hunting were to ever hope to be known as "conservation," there would have to be extremely close monitoring by scientific and state bodies regarding the health and legality of the hunt.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on September 14, 2021. May be an image of crocodile and text that says 'Financial incentives can hurt the population of a species Monitoring the population of a species takes a lot of resources for conservation groups and governments. It is possible that misinformation can lead to incorrect reporting of numbers to encourage hunting, or the financial benefits of continued hunting lead groups to inflate their reported numbers.'.

node.text:
PLEASE REPOST THIS ON YOUR STORY
•
⚠️PLEASE SHARE WITH YOUR FOLLOWERS TO STOP THIS ANIMAL CRUELTY!⚠️ Mocking and laughing at an innocent animal who’s in prison for life despite having done nothing wrong IS NOT OKAY! These poor animals are taken from their families out in the wild at a young age and then forced to spend the rest of their lives locked up, serving as entertainment for unaware tourists taking selfies. The fact that people still support and pay to visit these cruel places is tragic and it’s due to a lack of awareness so please use your social media platform for good and share this post with your followers to educate everyone as to why it’s SO cruel for these poor animals! WILD ANIMALS DO NOT DESERVE TO BE LOCKED UP FOR TOURISTS TO GAWK AT FOR THEIR ENTIRE LIVES…WE MUST WORK TOGETHER TO STOP THIS ANIMAL CRUELTY! Entertain your families in ways that does not inflict harm on others — teach them about we must respect and have compassion for all animals…not to be taken away from their families and out of the wild where they belong! Please share this sad video and tag people, celebrities, influencers news media who need to see and share this too, no animal deserves a lifetime of being locked up like this! #stopanimalcruelty #endanimalcruelty #animalsdeservebetter #wildanimals #wildandfree 
CC: @karmagawa

node.text:
Here’s a Happy quokka to welcome the weekend with a smile via @cruzysuzy 😊

The quokka, also known as the short-tailed scrub wallaby, is a little macropod about the size of a domestic cat. A quokka weighs 2.5 to 5.0 kg (5.5 to 11 lb) and is 40 to 54 cm (16 to 21 in) long with a 25-to-30 cm-long (9.8-to-12 in) tail.

It was first described by Dutch mariner Samuel Volckertzoon when he wrote of sighting "a wild cat" on Rottnest Island in 1658.

In the wild, the quokka’s roaming is restricted to a very small range in the South West of Western Australia, with a number of small scattered populations. One large population exists on Rottnest Island and a smaller population is on Bald Island near Albany.

📷 @cruzysuzy #nature
📍Rottnest Island, Australia

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on August 31, 2021. May be an image of dog and text that says 'ANIMAL ABUSE STATISTICS 2021 SWIPE'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on August 31, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, dog and text that says 'Statistics of animal abuse reveal that every 60 seconds, one animal suffers abuse. Close to 65% of all abused animals are dogs based on stats about animal abuse. There are two types of animal abuse: passive and active cruelty.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on August 31, 2021. May be an image of animal and text that says 'Every year, more than 115 million animals in the world are used for laboratory experiments. Every year, US labs abuse more than 19,000 cats. Denmark slaughtered 15-17 million animals for mink fur that tested positive for Covid-19.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on August 31, 2021. May be an image of cat and text that says 'Approximately 75,000 dogs are tortured in US labs every year. It's estimated that the lifetime prevalence of animal abuse in US adults is 1.8% according to domestic animal abuse statistics.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on August 31, 2021. May be an image of cat and text that says 'Statistics on animal cruelty reveal that very year, more than 10 million animals die from abuse in the US alone. Every year, more than 6.5 million animals enter animal shelters according to animal abuse statistics in the United States.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on August 31, 2021. May be an image of dog and text that says 'The latest animal abuse stats reveal that each year, the US kills over 3 million mink for fur. Over the last decade, there've been 483 drug- positive Greyhounds in Florida alone.'.

Photo by Plant A Tree Co. on August 31, 2021. May be an image of animal and text that says 'On average, 250,000 animals every year are victims of animal hoarding. Statistics on animal abuse reveal that there are over 10,000 puppy mills in the United States.'.
